      {
        "id": "q8",
        "questionSubtype": "longAnswer",
        "question": "Explain the difference between Rational and Irrational numbers based on their decimal expansions. Provide one example of each and explain why they fit their respective categories.",
        "answer": "Rational numbers have decimal expansions that either terminate (end) or repeat a pattern (e.g., 0.5 or 0.333...). They can be written as p/q. Example: 1/2 = 0.5 (terminating). Irrational numbers have non-terminating and non-repeating decimal expansions (e.g., 1.414...) and cannot be written as p/q. Example: √2 ≈ 1.414... (never repeats).",
        "expectedLength": "Clear distinction, examples for both, and reasoning for each",
